 is generally regarded, with  St Peter , as co-founder of the Christian Church. Born in Tarsus, and originally named <i>Saul</i>, he was both a Roman citizen and a Jew, and at first found employment as a minor official persecuting Christians. He was converted to Christianity by a vision of Christ while on the road to Damascus, and thereafter undertook extensive missionary journeys, converting people, especially Gentiles, to Christianity all over the eastern Mediterranean. His preaching aroused considerable official hostility, and eventually he was beheaded at Rome in about   ad  65 . He is the author of the fourteen epistles to churches and individuals which form part of the New Testament. It has been in continuous use in the British Isles since the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Paulus","meanings":["From Latin <i>Paulus</i>, a Roman family name, originally a nickname meaning ‘small’, used in the post-classical period as a given name. Pre-eminently this is the name of the saint who is generally regarded, with  St Peter , as co-founder of the Christian Church. Born in Tarsus, and originally named <i>Saul</i>, he was both a Roman citizen and a Jew, and at first found employment as a minor official persecuting Christians. He was converted to Christianity by a vision of Christ while on the road to Damascus, and thereafter undertook extensive missionary journeys, converting people, especially Gentiles, to Christianity all over the eastern Mediterranean. His preaching aroused considerable official hostility, and eventually he was beheaded at Rome in about   ad  65 . He is the author of the fourteen epistles to churches and individuals which form part of the New Testament. It has been in continuous use in the British Isles since the 16th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When The Free Booter Paul MacIntyre was born in 1345, in Kincardine, Ross-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, The Red Olaf MacIntyre, was 25 and his mother, Lady MacIntyre, was 23. He married Ha